# Web-pages frontend rules

Apply when creating or editing any page in this repo. See README.md for full workflow and execution modes.

---

## When developing a new page — apply all instructions

When developing any **new page**, you **must apply every section** of this instruction file. Do not skip or assume any rule. Use this as a run-through:

1. **Execution context** — Use Figma as sole source of truth (or content-docs when provided); build from the design/reference.
2. **When no directory exists** — Follow README (choose case, run setup); link to `../source/zohocustom.css` and `../source/product.css`; never copy or edit `source/`.
3. **File naming** — Entry file is always `index.html`; stylesheet is always `style.css`; JS is always `script.js`. No scratch, backup, or test files in page directories.
4. **Images and SVGs — ALWAYS use placeholders** — Never embed real image URLs or local asset files during development. Every `<img>` and every CSS `background-image` must use a placeholder. No `assets/` folder should be created or populated during development.
5. **HTML** — Semantic elements; `.page-container` > `<section>` > `.content-wrap`; `.act-btn` on all CTAs; no inline styles or handlers; one H1, correct heading order; `alt` on images, `<label>` for inputs.
6. **CSS** — Only `style.css`; check `zohocustom.css` for font/title/p/a styles; do not set styles for `.content-wrap` or `.act-btn`; desktop first with all six breakpoints; prefer `var(--...)` tokens; apply the global typography and spacing system.
7. **Spacing system** — Use the standard spacing values for section padding, card padding, and grid gaps. Do not invent arbitrary values.
8. **JavaScript** — Add `script.js` only if the design has interactivity; `DOMContentLoaded` or jQuery; short page-specific init may be inline at the bottom of `<body>`.
9. **Accessibility & responsiveness** — Keyboard focus, visible focus states, no horizontal scroll, responsive images.
10. **Validation checklist** — Before considering the page complete, run through the full checklist.
11. **Post-development** — Open the page in a browser tab so the user can verify the result.

If any instruction is unclear, refer to the detailed section below. **All instructions in this file apply to every page.**

---

## Execution context

- **Figma → Code (primary):** When a Figma design exists, treat the Figma file as the **sole source of truth** for layout, sections, spacing, and visuals. Do not rely on prior session decisions; inspect the design and build from it.
- **Content-docs / Revamp:** When content reference docs (e.g. in `docs/` or a brief) are provided instead of or alongside Figma, use the docs as the **content source** — structure copy, headings, and lists from the reference. Match layout to project patterns (`.page-container` > `<section>` > `.content-wrap`) and existing style; add sections only where the content requires them. Flag missing critical content (e.g. no hero headline, no CTA text) before inventing copy.

