## When no directory exists

- Use the **Common Cases — When No Directory Exists** section in README: choose Product/feature, Marketing, Glossary, Pricing, or Standalone.
- Run the one-time setup commands from README. **Do not copy** from `source/`; pages that need Zoho chrome **link** to `../source/zohocustom.css` and `../source/product.css` in HTML. Never edit files in `source/`.

---

## File naming and directory conventions

- **Entry file:** Always `index.html`. No alternative entry filenames.
- **Stylesheet:** Always `style.css` (not `styles.css`, not `main.css`). One stylesheet per page. If a page requires additional CSS modules (e.g. a self-contained component), name them clearly after their purpose (e.g. `pricing.css`) and document why a second file is needed.
- **JavaScript:** Always `script.js` as the primary file. For complex pages requiring a separate module, name it after its purpose (e.g. `pricing.js`). Never use generic or editor-generated filenames.
- **Assets:** All images and SVGs go in an `assets/` subdirectory within the page folder. Reference them as `./assets/filename.ext`. Never place asset files loose in the page root.
- **Directory names:** Use kebab-case (e.g. `glossary-embedded-api`). Avoid spaces and special characters in folder names.
- **No scratch or temporary files:** Never commit `Untitled-*`, `*.backup`, `test*.html`, or any file with shell metacharacters in its name. Use version control for history — backup files are not a substitute.

---

## Images and SVGs — always use placeholders during development

> **This is a hard rule. It applies to every page, every section, every component.**

During UI development, use the **single approved Zoho placeholder URL** for all provisional assets
(images, icons, logos, avatars, banner backgrounds). See `z_workflow/Rulesbook.md` §2.8.

```
https://prezohoweb.zoho.com/
```

Do **not** use `placehold.co`, local file paths, or other CDN URLs for placeholders.

### Why
- One consistent placeholder keeps scaffold output visually aligned across pages.
- Real production URLs break when assets are not yet available.
- Creating an `assets/` folder with dummy files pollutes the directory and gets committed by mistake.
- Placeholders keep the layout honest — `width`/`height` from Figma still define dimensions.

### Three asset types — handle each differently

#### 1. Content images (`<img>` tags)
Use the universal placeholder URL. Always include `width`, `height`, a descriptive `alt`, and a `<!-- TODO -->` comment.

```html
<!-- TODO: replace with final asset -->
<img
  src="https://prezohoweb.zoho.com/"
  alt="Dashboard showing sales pipeline analytics"
  width="1200"
  height="600">
```

#### 2. CSS decorative backgrounds (`background-image: url(...)`)
Use the universal placeholder URL with required background properties and a `/* TODO */` comment.

```css
.banner::after {
    /* TODO: replace with final background asset */
    background-image: url('https://prezohoweb.zoho.com/');
    background-size: cover;
    background-position: center top;
    background-repeat: no-repeat;
}
```

#### 3. UI control icons (close button, arrows, small decorative icons, icon sprites)
Use the same placeholder URL as `background-image` on the icon holder. Keep dimensions and position intact.

```css
.icon-close {
    /* TODO: replace with final icon asset */
    background-image: url('https://prezohoweb.zoho.com/');
    background-size: contain;
    background-position: center;
    background-repeat: no-repeat;
    width: 18px;
    height: 18px;
}
```

#### 4. Inline SVG illustrations
Use a minimal grey rectangle as a stand-in. Do not copy SVG markup from other projects or external sources.

```html
<!-- TODO: replace with final illustration -->
<svg width="40" height="40" viewBox="0 0 40 40" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
    <rect width="40" height="40" rx="8" fill="#CBD5E1"/>
</svg>
```

### Additional rules
- **No `assets/` folder during development.** Do not create or populate an `assets/` directory. When the user provides final assets, place them in `assets/` and replace all placeholders at that point.
- **Dimensions must match the design.** Use the Figma-specified width and height so the layout is accurate — never use a generic 100×100 when the design shows a 1200×600 hero image.
- **`linear-gradient` is not an asset.** CSS gradients used for backgrounds or text fills are design tokens, not images — leave them as-is.

